        <b><span id="titleLabel">1.4 - Franchise power: Understanding the DNA of the industry's greatest games</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Wednesday, May 10, 3:30 PM - 5:00 PM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 404AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">Creating a single blockbuster title is hard enough, but creating a game that can spawn an ongoing series is doubly hard. For every Need for Speed and Grand Theft Auto, there's a one-shot wonder that died after the first iteration or sequel. What separates games that have franchise potential from those that can't endure even a single update? What is it about a game's characters, world, set of challenges, or reward system that gives it franchise legs? And is there a downside to annualizing a title year after year? This session will look at four of the most significant franchises of the past decade and will determine the key elements behind their success. How was their superstar status maintained over the course of years, through platform updates and generational shifts among gamers? How was feature innovation used to maintain a game's relevance with consumers? In what ways can sequels enable innovation, giving designers their best opportunity for showcasing a killer app? Hear key members of each game's design team share their unique recipe for creating games that remain top sellers release after release.</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td width="18%" class="tableCell">Moderator:</td>
                <td class="tableCell"><span id="moderatorLabel">Jeff Green, Editor-in-Chief, Computer Gaming World - Ziff Davis</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell">Panelists:</td>
